"Katz R.W.","Techniques for estimating uncertainty in climate change scenarios and impact studies",2002,"Climate Research","20","2",,"167","185",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0036321570&partnerID=40&md5=3d7dca5ca8ff2e5c9d76c37fc32c4cb7","Environmental/Societal Impacts Group, National Center for Atmospheric Res., Boulder, CO 80307, United States","Katz, R.W., Environmental/Societal Impacts Group, National Center for Atmospheric Res., Boulder, CO 80307, United States","Methodology for quantifying uncertainty in global climate change studies is reviewed. The focus is on recent developments in statistics, such as hierarchical modeling and Markov chain Monte Carlo simulation techniques, that could enable more full-fledged uncertainty analyses to be performed as part of integrated assessments of climate change and its impacts. First an overview of uncertainty analysis, including its sources and how it propagates, is provided. Presently employed techniques in climate change assessments, such as sensitivity, scenario, and Monte Carlo simulation analyses, are then surveyed. Next alternative approaches, based on more formal statistical theory (especially the Bayesian statistical paradigm), are described. Finally, some tentative recommendations on strategies for achieving the goal of more reliably quantifying uncertainty in global climate change are made.","Aggregation/scaling; Bayesian statistics; Extremes; Monte Carlo simulation; Scenario analysis; Sensitivity analysis","climate change; estimation method; global change; statistical analysis; uncertainty analysis",,,,,,"Adams, R.M., Crocker, T.D., Katz, R.W., Assessing the adequacy of natural science information: A Bayesian approach (1984) Rev Econ Stat, 66, pp. 568-575; Alcamo, J., Kreileman, E., Emission scenarios and global climate protection (1996) Global Environ Change, 6, pp. 305-334; Alcamo, J., Kreileman, E., Leemans, R., Global models meet global policy (1996) Global Environ Change, 6, pp. 25